# NIT Cyber Analysis — Network Intrusion Detection using CIC-IDS2017

Research project on network intrusion detection using the CIC-IDS2017 dataset.
Covers data preprocessing, exploratory analysis, and deep learning classification
across 15 traffic categories (14 attack types + benign).

---

## Dataset

CIC-IDS2017 — Canadian Institute for Cybersecurity
8 CSV files, ~2.8M network flow records, 78 features + label
Download: https://www.unb.ca/cic/datasets/ids-2017.html
*(CSV files not tracked in this repo due to size)*

---

## Project Structure
├── 01_pre-processing.ipynb   # Data cleaning pipeline

├── 02_EDA.ipynb              # Exploratory analysis

├── 03_modelling.ipynb        # Encoding, scaling, SMOTE, model training

└── README.md

---

## Work Division

**Undergraduate contribution (this repo):**
- Loaded and merged all 8 CSV files into a single dataframe (~2.8M rows)
- Handled missing values, infinite values (division-by-zero in flow features), and duplicate rows
- Stripped column name and label whitespace inconsistencies present in the raw dataset
- EDA: label distribution, binary vs multi-class split, correlation heatmap, outlier boxplots, feature distribution analysis
- Modelling prep: Label Encoding, feature selection, stratified train-test split (80/20), StandardScaler, SMOTE

**PhD scholar contribution:**
- Deep learning model architecture design and training
- Hyperparameter tuning and evaluation
- Results analysis and benchmarking

---

## Pipeline
Raw CSVs → Merge → Clean → EDA → Encode → Split → Scale → SMOTE → Model

---

## Setup

```bash
pip install pandas numpy matplotlib seaborn scikit-learn imbalanced-learn
jupyter notebook
```

Run notebooks in order: `01` → `02` → `03`

